<td class="article-body"><P>23.07.05</P>
<P>There has been a lot of confusion in the press and between various reports as to whether Marat had surgery or treatment.</P>
<P>Gerard Tsobanian says it is a treatment - Shamil Tarpischev says surgery - which is correct?</P>
<P>After a bit of investigation I have come to some conclusions. Please note this is only my opinion - not an official statement.</P>
<P>The Isokinetic is noted for helping soccer players who are always having problems with their knees. Another sport that has lots of knee problems is rugby and as a rugby fan I came across this bit of information regarding the treatment that a favourite rugby player of mine is getting.</P>
<P>Quote<BR></P>
<P style="LINE-HEIGHT: 10pt"><SPAN style="FONT-SIZE: 8pt; COLOR: blue; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Sharks Team Doctor Craig Roberts announced on Thursday that James's knee injury was being treated with a new technique of injections that act as a potent stimulator of cartilage growth. The Sharks flyhalf had the first injection in his left knee last week, and will have another in three months time. <?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = "urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office" /><o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P style="LINE-HEIGHT: 10pt"><SPAN style="FONT-SIZE: 8pt; COLOR: blue; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">The treatment is being administered by one of <?xml:namespace prefix = st1 ns = "urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:smarttags" /><st1:City w:st="on"><st1:place w:st="on">Johannesburg</st1:place></st1:City>'s leading orthopedic specialists in conjunction with a recovery treatment programme by the Sharks Medical Team and biokenticists. <o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P style="LINE-HEIGHT: 10pt"><SPAN style="FONT-SIZE: 8pt; COLOR: blue; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">James suffers from a defect in the cartilage under his kneecap, sustained during a knock on the knee. As a result, he has a gap in the cartilage that results in fluid flowing through to his knee every time he runs. <o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P style="LINE-HEIGHT: 10pt"><SPAN style="FONT-SIZE: 8pt; COLOR: blue; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">This in turn makes the knee "puffy", making it difficult for him to train and exercise. Due to the fluid in the knee his muscles shut down and weaken, placing the ligaments in his knee at risk. <o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P style="LINE-HEIGHT: 10pt"><SPAN style="FONT-SIZE: 8pt; COLOR: blue; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">"The PGF (platelet derived growth factor) injections are literally designed to plug the gap in the cartilage by stimulating cartilage growth " explained Roberts. <o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P>Unquote</P>
<P>To me the main factor is the PGF(platelet derived growth factor) injections! So I did a bit more investigation and found this explanation of PGF.<BR><BR>Quote<BR></P>
<H1 style="MARGIN: auto 0cm"><SPAN style="COLOR: yellow; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">platelet-derived growth factor<o:p></o:p></SPAN></H1><SPAN style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">
<P><SPAN style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: silver; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">(Science: growth factor) The <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/major"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>major</U></SPAN></A> <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/mitogen"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>mitogen</U></SPAN></A> in <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/serum"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>serum</U></SPAN></A> for <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/growth"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>growth</U></SPAN></A> in <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/culture"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>culture</U></SPAN></A> of <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/cells"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>cells</U></SPAN></A> of <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/connective_tissue"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>connective tissue</U></SPAN></A> <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/origin"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>origin</U></SPAN></A>. It consists of 2 different but <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/homologous"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>homologous</U></SPAN></A> <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/polypeptides"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>polypeptides</U></SPAN></A> A and B (~30,000 D) <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/linked"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>linked</U></SPAN></A> by <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/disulphide_bonds"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>disulphide bonds</U></SPAN></A>. Believed to <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/play"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>play</U></SPAN></A> a <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/role"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>role</U></SPAN></A> in <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/wound"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>wound</U></SPAN></A> <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/healing"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>healing</U></SPAN></A>. <o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P><SPAN style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: silver; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">It is carried in the <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/alpha"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>alpha</U></SPAN></A>-<A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/granules"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>granules</U></SPAN></A> of <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/platelets"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>platelets</U></SPAN></A> and is released when <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/platelets"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>platelets</U></SPAN></A> adhere to traumatised <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/tissues"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>tissues</U></SPAN></A>. <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/connective_tissue_cells"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>Connective tissue cells</U></SPAN></A> <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/near"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>near</U></SPAN></A> the traumatised <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/region"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>region</U></SPAN></A> <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/respond"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>respond</U></SPAN></A> by initiating the <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/process"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>process</U></SPAN></A> of <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/replication"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>replication</U></SPAN></A>. <o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P><SPAN style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: silver; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">The <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/b_chain"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>B chain</U></SPAN></A> is almost <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/identical"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>identical</U></SPAN></A> in <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/sequence"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>sequence</U></SPAN></A> to p28sis, the transforming <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/protein"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>protein</U></SPAN></A> of <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/simian"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>simian</U></SPAN></A> <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/sarcoma_virus"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>sarcoma virus</U></SPAN></A>, that can <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/transform"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>transform</U></SPAN></A> only those <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/cells"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>cells</U></SPAN></A> that <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/express"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>express</U></SPAN></A> <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/receptors"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>receptors</U></SPAN></A> for <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/platelet"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>platelet</U></SPAN></A> derived <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/growth_factor"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>growth factor</U></SPAN></A>, suggesting that <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/transformation"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>transformation</U></SPAN></A> is caused by <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/autocrine"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>autocrine</U></SPAN></A> <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/stimulation"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>stimulation</U></SPAN></A>. The receptor is a <A href="http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/tyrosine_kinase"><SPAN style="COLOR: silver"><U>tyrosine kinase</U></SPAN></A>. <o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P><SPAN style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: silver; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Acronym: PDGF <o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P></SPAN>Unquote</P>
<P>Now following on with that it would appear that Marat is indeed undergoing treatment and not had surgery. So how did the "surgery" come into it. Maybe a wrong translation given all the various languages involved. Or another thought as Marat does not like needles and this is obviously a very deep injection - a local anesthetic was administered before the injection. If this is what happened then it would explain the pain Marat had to start with immediately after the injection&nbsp;and then&nbsp;the pain&nbsp;eased.</P>
<P>So to put it in simple terms a substance has been injected into the affected ligament to promote replication of the cells and thus speed up a healing of the tear in the ligament.</P>
<P>Therefore the truth is Marat is receiving treatment after a minor local "surgery" on his knee.</P>
<P>And if you are still confused -&nbsp;just be grateful that&nbsp; it is a process intent on getting Marat's knee back in shape so he can continue playing and making us all happy to see him back on the tennis playing field.</P>
<P>Please note that I must stress that this is not an official statement - just my attempt to try and give a logical explanation to all the speculation.</P>
<P>Webmaster</P></td>
